{"_id": "19473078|None", "id": "19473078", "infons": {}, "passages": [{"infons": {"journal": "Genet Test Mol Biomarkers; 2009 Jun; 13(3) 339-42. doi:10.1089/gtmb.2008.0129", "year": "2009", "type": "title", "authors": "Dresner-Pollak R, Kinnar T, Friedlander Y, Sharon N, Rosenmann H, Pollak A", "section": "Title"}, "offset": 0, "text": "Estrogen receptor beta gene variant is associated with vascular dementia in elderly women.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "3", "infons": {"identifier": "2100", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "1100"}, "text": "Estrogen receptor beta", "locations": [{"offset": 0, "length": 22}]}, {"id": "4", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D015140", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "vascular dementia", "locations": [{"offset": 55, "length": 17}]}, {"id": "5", "infons": {"identifier": "9606", "type": "Species"}, "text": "women", "locations": [{"offset": 84, "length": 5}]}], "relations": []}, {"infons": {"type": "abstract", "section": "Abstract"}, "offset": 91, "text": "OBJECTIVE: Alzheimer's disease (AD) and vascular dementia (VaD) are the main causes of dementia. Postmenopausal estrogen deficiency was suggested as a contributor to cognitive decline; however, replacement therapy failed to prove beneficial in its prevention or therapy. Sequence variants in the estrogen receptor alpha gene (ESR1) and beta gene (ESR2) may alter the effects of estrogen. METHODS: This is a case-control association study of sporadic AD, VaD, and single-nucleotide polymorphisms in ESR1 (rs2234693 and rs9340799), the TA dinucleotide repeat in the ESR1 promoter, and the rs4986938 single-nucleotide polymorphism in ESR2. Two hundred forty-six women (118 AD, age 83 +/- 7; 60 VaD, age 82 +/- 6; and 68 cognitively intact, age 81 +/- 7) residing in nursing homes were studied. The association of genotypes and AD or VaD was determined by logistic regression analysis adjusted for age and ethnic origin. RESULTS: An association of VaD and ESR2 rs4986938 was found. Carriers of each A allele had a 1.7 increased risk compared to carriers of the G allele (odds ratio 1.71, 95% confidence interval 1-2.95). The ApoE epsilon 4 allele was associated with AD (odds ratio 3.35, confidence interval 1.44-7.82), but not with VaD. No association of AD or VaD with ESR1 genotypes or haplotypes was detected. CONCLUSIONS: The ESR2 rs4986938 polymorphism is associated with susceptibility for VaD in elderly Jewish women. These results need to be confirmed in replicate studies in other populations.", "sentences": [], "annotations": [{"id": "32", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000544", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "Alzheimer's disease", "locations": [{"offset": 102, "length": 19}]}, {"id": "33", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000544", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "AD", "locations": [{"offset": 123, "length": 2}]}, {"id": "34", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D015140", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "vascular dementia", "locations": [{"offset": 131, "length": 17}]}, {"id": "35", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D003704", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "dementia", "locations": [{"offset": 178, "length": 8}]}, {"id": "36", "infons": {"identifier": "2099", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "47906"}, "text": "estrogen receptor alpha", "locations": [{"offset": 387, "length": 23}]}, {"id": "37", "infons": {"identifier": "2099", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "47906"}, "text": "ESR1", "locations": [{"offset": 417, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "38", "infons": {"identifier": "2100", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "1100"}, "text": "ESR2", "locations": [{"offset": 438, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "39", "infons": {"identifier": "MESH:D000544", "type": "Disease"}, "text": "AD", "locations": [{"offset": 541, "length": 2}]}, {"id": "40", "infons": {"identifier": "2099", "type": "Gene", "ncbi_homologene": "47906"}, "text": "ESR1", "locations": [{"offset": 589, "length": 4}]}, {"id": "41", "infons": {"identifier": "rs2234693", "type": "Mutation", "subtype": "SNP"}, "text": "rs2234693", "locati